<TITLE> Clampdown against 3000 illegal buildings in Dhaka </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, June 22 (bdnews24.com)--State minister for housing and public works Abdul Mannan said Monday that the government had begun taking action against approximately 3000 buildings in the capital that do not meet RAJUK standards. Responding to questions from the parliament floor, the minister added that action would be taken in line with the Buildings Act and Dhaka city building regulations. In other parliamentary news, education minister Nurul Islam Nahid announced that free books would be provided to all secondary level students from the 2010 session onwards. In addition new books in all subjects will be provided for primary school level students in 2010. The education minister also expanded on the Tk 112 crore Monthly Payment Order allocations in the proposed budget, saying enlistment initiatives would be made following recommendations from a government committee. Finally, state minister for science and ICT Yafes Osman said a memorandum of understanding had been signed between Bangladesh and Russia to meet the nation's electricity needs through a nuclear power plant project. The project will take between five to seven years to be implemented, said Osman. bdnews24.c
